The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                               CRICKET BRIEFS
                  
	Calcutta: The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) on Wednesday recommended opener Gautam Gambhir and womens team captain Jhulan Gosawmi for the prestigious Arjuna Awards. The decision to nominate the two players was taken at the BCCIs working committee meeting in Mumbai.        
	Calcutta: The Indian cricketers will have a much-needed break as the BCCI on Wednesday cancelled its tour of Zimbabwe where they were scheduled to play a triangular series in July. The visit to Zimbabwe has been dropped  They will have to find the third team for the series, BCCI secretary N. Srinivasan said after the Boards working committee meeting in Mumbai.           
	Calcutta: The Kings XI Punjab have included Sri Lankan all-rounder Nuwan Kulasekara as a replacement for Australian Shaun Marsh, who injured his left hamstring during his countrys ongoing one-day series against Pakistan.        
	Durban: Former South African cricket board chief Ali Bacher has urged the ICC to create a permanent window for the Indian Premier League in its calendar as the Twenty20 tournament has become the No.1 event in world cricket.        
	Mumbai: The BCCI has decided to stage its planned inter-corporate tournament, comprising of 16 teams, this September and would hold a meeting with representatives of banks, public sector undertakings and other corporates within a month.        
	London: Yorkshire pacer Tim Bresnan was a surprise inclusion in the England squad announced on Wednesday for the first Test against West Indies. Ravi Bopara was also named in the 12-man squad.            
	Calcutta: The England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) approved plans for a two-division P20 competition starting in June 2010, on Wednesday. The P20 will be staged in June each year.        
	Abu Dhabi: Pakistani off-spinner Saeed Ajmal has been fined an undisclosed sum of his match fee and warned because of his comments about Australian all-rounder Shane Watson.  
